# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: x10-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] This is a property of a system—whether a program, computer, or a network—where there is a separate execution point or "thread of control" for each process.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] A *concurrent system* is one where a computation can advance without waiting for all other computations to complete.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing is a form of modular programming.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] In its paradigm an overall computation is factored into subcomputations that may be executed concurrently.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Pioneers in the field of concurrent computing include Edsger Dijkstra, Per Brinch Hansen, and C.A.R.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The concept of concurrent computing is frequently confused with the related but distinct concept of parallel computing, although both can be described as "multiple processes executing *during the same period of time*".
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] By contrast, concurrent computing consists of process *lifetimes* overlapping, but execution does not happen at the same instant.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The goal here is to model processes that happen concurrently, like multiple clients accessing a server at the same time.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Structuring software systems as composed of multiple concurrent, communicating parts can be useful for tackling complexity, regardless of whether the parts can be executed in parallel.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] In this way, multiple processes are part-way through execution at a single instant, but only one process is being executed at that instant.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computations *may* be executed in parallel, for example, by assigning each process to a separate processor or processor core, or distributing a computation across a network.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The exact timing of when tasks in a concurrent system are executed depends on the scheduling, and tasks need not always be executed concurrently.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The word "sequential" is used as an antonym for both "concurrent" and "parallel"; when these are explicitly distinguished, *concurrent/sequential* and *parallel/serial* are used as opposing pairs.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] A schedule in which tasks execute one at a time (serially, no parallelism), without interleaving (sequentially, no concurrency: no task begins until the prior task ends) is called a *serial schedule*.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] A set of tasks that can be scheduled serially is *serializable*, which simplifies concurrency control.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The main challenge in designing concurrent programs is concurrency control: ensuring the correct sequencing of the interactions or communications between different computational executions, and coordinating access to resources that are shared among executions.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Potential problems include race conditions, deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Suppose `balance = 500`, and two concurrent *threads* make the calls `withdraw(300)` and `withdraw(350)`.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] If line 3 in both operations executes before line 5 both operations will find that `balance >= withdrawal` evaluates to `true`, and execution will proceed to subtracting the withdrawal amount.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] However, since both processes perform their withdrawals, the total amount withdrawn will end up being more than the original balance.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] These sorts of problems with shared resources benefit from the use of concurrency control, or non-blocking algorithms.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Introduced in 1962, Petri nets were an early attempt to codify the rules of concurrent execution.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Dataflow theory later built upon these, and Dataflow architectures were created to physically implement the ideas of dataflow theory.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Beginning in the late 1970s, process calculi such as Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) were developed to permit algebraic reasoning about systems composed of interacting components.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The π-calculus added the capability for reasoning about dynamic topologies.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Input/output automata were introduced in 1987.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Logics such as Lamport's TLA+, and mathematical models such as traces and Actor event diagrams, have also been developed to describe the behavior of concurrent systems.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Software transactional memory borrows from database theory the concept of atomic transactions and applies them to memory accesses.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages and multiprocessor programs must have a consistency model (also known as a memory model).
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The consistency model defines rules for how operations on computer memory occur and how results are produced.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] One of the first consistency models was Leslie Lamport's sequential consistency model.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Sequential consistency is the property of a program that its execution produces the same results as a sequential program.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Specifically, a program is sequentially consistent if "the results of any execution is the same as if the operations of all the processors were executed in some sequential order, and the operations of each individual processor appear in this sequence in the order specified by its program".
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] A number of different methods can be used to implement concurrent programs, such as implementing each computational execution as an operating system process, or implementing the computational processes as a set of threads within a single operating system process.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] In some concurrent computing systems, communication between the concurrent components is hidden from the programmer (e.g., by using futures), while in others it must be handled explicitly.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The exchange of messages may be carried out asynchronously, or may use a synchronous "rendezvous" style in which the sender blocks until the message is received.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Asynchronous message passing may be reliable or unreliable (sometimes referred to as "send and pray").
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Message-passing concurrency tends to be far easier to reason about than shared-memory concurrency, and is typically considered a more robust form of concurrent programming.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Shared memory and message passing concurrency have different performance characteristics.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Typically (although not always), the per-process memory overhead and task switching overhead is lower in a message passing system, but the overhead of message passing is greater than for a procedure call.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] These differences are often overwhelmed by other performance factors.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing developed out of earlier work on railroads and telegraphy, from the 19th and early 20th century, and some terms date to this period, such as semaphores.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] These arose to address the question of how to handle multiple trains on the same railroad system (avoiding collisions and maximizing efficiency) and how to handle multiple transmissions over a given set of wires (improving efficiency), such as via time-division multiplexing (1870s).
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] The academic study of concurrent algorithms started in the 1960s, with Dijkstra (1965) credited with being the first paper in this field, identifying and solving mutual exclusion.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrency is pervasive in computing, occurring from low-level hardware on a single chip to worldwide networks.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] At the network level, networked systems are generally concurrent by their nature, as they consist of separate devices.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages are programming languages that use language constructs for concurrency.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] These constructs may involve multi-threading, support for distributed computing, message passing, shared resources (including shared memory) or futures and promises.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Such languages are sometimes described as *concurrency-oriented languages* or *concurrency-oriented programming languages* (COPL).
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Today, the most commonly used programming languages that have specific constructs for concurrency are Java and C#.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Both of these languages fundamentally use a shared-memory concurrency model, with locking provided by monitors (although message-passing models can and have been implemented on top of the underlying shared-memory model).
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Of the languages that use a message-passing concurrency model, Erlang was probably the most widely used in industry as of 2010.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Many concurrent programming languages have been developed more as research languages (e.g., Pict) rather than as languages for production use.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] However, languages such as Erlang, Limbo, and occam have seen industrial use at various times in the last 20 years.
[src:x10-language/concurrent-computing] Many other languages provide support for concurrency in the form of libraries, at levels roughly comparable with the above list.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] In computer programming, a **green thread** is a thread that is scheduled by a runtime library or virtual machine (VM) instead of natively by the underlying operating system (OS).
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Green threads emulate multithreaded environments without relying on any native OS abilities, and they are managed in user space instead of kernel space, enabling them to work in environments that do not have native thread support.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Green threads refers to the name of the original thread library for Java programming language (that was released in version 1.1 and then Green threads were abandoned in version 1.3 to native threads).
[src:x10-language/green-threads] It was designed by *The Green Team* at Sun Microsystems.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Green threads were briefly available in Java between 1997 and 2000.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Green threads share a single operating system thread through co-operative concurrency and can therefore not achieve parallelism performance gains like operating system threads.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] The main benefit of coroutines and green threads is ease of implementation.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] On a multi-core processor, native thread implementations can automatically assign work to multiple processors, whereas green thread implementations normally cannot.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Green threads can be started much faster on some VMs.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] On uniprocessor computers, however, the most efficient model has not yet been clearly determined.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] When a green thread executes a blocking system call, not only is that thread blocked, but all of the threads within the process are blocked.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] To avoid that problem, green threads must use non-blocking I/O or asynchronous I/O operations, although the increased complexity on the user side can be reduced if the virtual machine implementing the green threads spawns specific I/O processes (hidden to the user) for each I/O operation.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] In Java 1.1, green threads were the only threading model used by the Java virtual machine (JVM), at least on Solaris.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] As green threads have some limitations compared to native threads, subsequent Java versions dropped them in favor of native threads.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] An exception to this is the Squawk virtual machine, which is a mixture between an operating system for low-power devices and a Java virtual machine.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] It uses green threads to minimize the use of native code, and to support migrating its isolates.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Kilim and Quasar are open-source projects which implement green threads on later versions of the JVM by modifying the Java bytecode produced by the Java compiler (Quasar also supports Kotlin and Clojure).
[src:x10-language/green-threads] There are some other programming languages that implement equivalents of green threads instead of native threads.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] The Erlang virtual machine has what might be called *green processes* – they are like operating system processes (they do not share state like threads do) but are implemented within the Erlang Run Time System (erts).
[src:x10-language/green-threads] These are sometimes termed *green threads*, but have significant differences from standard green threads.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] In the case of GHC Haskell, a context switch occurs at the first allocation after a configurable timeout.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Most Smalltalk virtual machines do not count evaluation steps; however, the VM can still preempt the executing thread on external signals (such as expiring timers, or I/O becoming available).
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Other implementations, e.g., QKS Smalltalk, are always time-sharing.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Unlike most green thread implementations, QKS also supports preventing priority inversion.
[src:x10-language/green-threads] Virtual threads were introduced as a preview feature in Java 19 and stabilized in Java 21.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates systems administration (including network and security knowledge), parallel computing and distributed computing into a multidisciplinary field that combines digital electronics, computer architecture, system software, programming languages, algorithms and computational techniques.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] HPC technologies are the tools and systems used to implement and create high performance computing systems.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Since around 2005, HPC systems have shifted from supercomputing to computing clusters and grids.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Because of the need of networking in clusters and grids, High Performance Computing Technologies are achieved by the use of a collapsed network backbone, because the collapsed backbone architecture is simple to troubleshoot and upgrades can be applied to a single router as opposed to multiple ones.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates with data analytics in AI engineering workflows to generate new data streams that increase a simulation's ability to answer the "what if" questions.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] The term is most commonly associated with computing used for scientific research or computational science.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] A related term, high-performance technical computing (HPTC), generally refers to the engineering applications of cluster-based computing (such as computational fluid dynamics and the building and testing of virtual prototypes).
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] HPC has also been applied to business uses such as data warehouses, line of business (LOB) applications, and transaction processing.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] High-performance computing (HPC) as a term arose after the term "supercomputing".
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] HPC is sometimes used as a synonym for supercomputing; but, in other contexts, "supercomputer" is used to refer to a more powerful subset of "high-performance computers", and the term "supercomputing" becomes a subset of "high-performance computing".
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] The potential for confusion over the use of these terms is apparent.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Because most current applications are not designed for HPC technologies but are retrofitted, they are not designed or tested for scaling to more powerful processors or machines.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Since networking clusters and grids use multiple processors and computers, these scaling problems can cripple critical systems in future supercomputing systems.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Therefore, either the existing tools do not address the needs of the high performance computing community or the HPC community is unaware of these tools.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] In government and research institutions, scientists simulate galaxy formation and evolution, fusion energy, and global warming, as well as work to create more accurate short- and long-term weather forecasts.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] The world's tenth most powerful supercomputer in 2008, IBM Roadrunner (located at the United States Department of Energy's Los Alamos National Laboratory) simulated the performance, safety, and reliability of nuclear weapons and certifies their functionality.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] TOP500 ranks the world's 500 fastest high-performance computers, as measured by the High Performance LINPACK (HPL) benchmark.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Not all existing computers are ranked, either because they are ineligible (e.g., they cannot run the HPL benchmark) or because their owners have not submitted an HPL score (e.g., because they do not wish the size of their system to become public information, for defense reasons).
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] In addition, the use of the single LINPACK benchmark is controversial, in that no single measure can test all aspects of a high-performance computer.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] To help overcome the limitations of the LINPACK test, the U.S. government commissioned one of its originators, Jack Dongarra of the University of Tennessee, to create a suite of benchmark tests that includes LINPACK and others, called the HPC Challenge benchmark suite.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] This evolving suite has been used in some HPC procurements, but, because it is not reducible to a single number, it has been unable to overcome the publicity advantage of the less useful TOP500 LINPACK test.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] The TOP500 list is updated twice a year, once in June at the ISC European Supercomputing Conference and again at a US Supercomputing Conference in November.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Many ideas for the new wave of grid computing were originally borrowed from HPC.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Traditionally, HPC has involved an on-premises infrastructure, investing in supercomputers or computer clusters.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Over the last decade, cloud computing has grown in popularity for offering computer resources in the commercial sector regardless of their investment capabilities.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] Some characteristics like scalability and containerization also have raised interest in academia.
[src:x10-language/high-performance-computing] However security in the cloud concerns such as data confidentiality are still considered when deciding between cloud or on-premise HPC resources.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM was founded in 1911 as the Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company (CTR), a holding company of manufacturers of record-keeping and measuring systems.
[src:x10-language/ibm] It was renamed "International Business Machines" in 1924 and soon became the leading manufacturer of punch-card tabulating systems.
[src:x10-language/ibm] During the 1960s and 1970s, the IBM mainframe, exemplified by the System/360 and its successors, was the world's dominant computing platform, with the company producing 80 percent of computers in the U.S. and 70 percent of computers worldwide.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Embracing both business and scientific computing, System/360 was the first family of computers designed to cover a complete range of applications from small to large.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM entered the microcomputer market in 1981 with the IBM Personal Computer; its architecture remains the basis for the majority of personal computers sold today.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company later also found success in the laptop space with the ThinkPad.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Since the 1990s, IBM has concentrated on computer services, software, supercomputers, and scientific research; it sold its microcomputer division to Lenovo in 2005.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM continues to develop mainframes, and its supercomputers have consistently ranked among the most powerful in the world in the 21st century.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company has made inroads in advanced computer chips, quantum computing, artificial intelligence, and data infrastructure.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM employees and alumni have won various recognitions for their scientific research and inventions, including six Nobel Prizes and six Turing Awards.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM originated with several technological innovations developed and commercialized in the late 19th century.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Pitrap patented the computing scale in 1885; Alexander Dey invented the dial recorder (1888); Herman Hollerith patented the Electric Tabulating Machine (1889); and Willard Bundy invented a time clock to record workers' arrival and departure times on a paper tape (1889).
[src:x10-language/ibm] On June 16, 1911, their four companies were amalgamated in New York State by Charles Ranlett Flint forming a fifth company, the Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company (CTR) based in Endicott, New York.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The five companies had 1,300 employees and offices and plants in Endicott and Binghamton, New York; Dayton, Ohio; Detroit, Michigan; Washington, D.C.; and Toronto, Canada.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Collectively, the companies manufactured a wide array of machinery for sale and lease, ranging from commercial scales and industrial time recorders, meat and cheese slicers, to tabulators and punched cards.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Watson, Sr., fired from the National Cash Register Company (NCR) by John Henry Patterson, called on Flint and, in 1914, was offered a position at CTR.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Watson joined CTR as general manager and then, 11 months later, was made President when antitrust cases relating to his time at NCR were resolved.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Having learned Patterson's pioneering business practices, Watson proceeded to put the stamp of NCR onto CTR's companies.
[src:x10-language/ibm] He implemented sales conventions, "generous sales incentives, a focus on customer service, an insistence on well-groomed, dark-suited salesmen and had an evangelical fervor for instilling company pride and loyalty in every worker".
[src:x10-language/ibm] His favorite slogan, "THINK", became a mantra for each company's employees.
[src:x10-language/ibm] During Watson's first four years, revenues reached $9 million ($167 million today) and the company's operations expanded to Europe, South America, Asia and Australia.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Watson never liked the clumsy hyphenated name "Computing-Tabulating-Recording Company" and chose to replace it with the more expansive title "International Business Machines" which had previously been used as the name of CTR's Canadian Division; the name was changed on February 14, 1924.
[src:x10-language/ibm] By 1933, most of the subsidiaries had been merged into one company, IBM.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The Nazis made extensive use of Hollerith punch card and alphabetical accounting equipment and IBM's majority-owned German subsidiary, Deutsche Hollerith Maschinen GmbH (Dehomag), supplied this equipment from the early 1930s.
[src:x10-language/ibm] This equipment was critical to Nazi efforts to categorize citizens of both Germany and other nations that fell under Nazi control through ongoing censuses.
[src:x10-language/ibm] These census data were used to facilitate the round-up of Jews and other targeted groups, and to catalog their movements through the machinery of the Holocaust, including internment in the concentration camps.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Edwin Black contends in *IBM and the Holocaust* that IBM's dealings with Nazis through its New York City headquarters persisted during World War II.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Nazi concentration camps operated a Hollerith department called Hollerith Abteilung, which had IBM machines, including calculating and sorting machines.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM as a military contractor produced 6% of the M1 Carbine rifles used in World War II, about 346,500 of them, between August 1943 and May 1944.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM built the Automatic Sequence Controlled Calculator, an electromechanical computer, during World War II.
[src:x10-language/ibm] It offered its first commercial stored-program computer, the vacuum tube based IBM 701, in 1952.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The IBM 305 RAMAC introduced the hard disk drive in 1956.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company switched to transistorized designs with the 7000 and 1400 series, beginning in 1958.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The 1400 series was the first to deploy over 10000 units, making it its most successful computer device at the time.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1956, the company demonstrated the first practical example of artificial intelligence when Arthur L.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Samuel of IBM's Poughkeepsie, New York, laboratory programmed an IBM 704 not merely to play checkers but "learn" from its own experience.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1957, the FORTRAN scientific programming language was announced.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1961, IBM developed the SABRE reservation system for American Airlines and introduced the highly successful Selectric typewriter.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Also in 1961, IBM used the IBM 7094 to generate the first song sung completely by a computer using synthesizers.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The song was Daisy Bell (Bicycle Built for Two).
[src:x10-language/ibm] The recording is now in the United States National Recording Registry.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1963, IBM employees and computers helped NASA track the orbital flights of the Mercury astronauts.
[src:x10-language/ibm] A year later, it moved its corporate headquarters from New York City to Armonk, New York.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The latter half of the 1960s saw IBM continue its support of space exploration, participating in the 1965 Gemini flights, 1966 Saturn flights, and 1969 lunar mission.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM also developed and manufactured the Saturn V's Instrument Unit and Apollo spacecraft guidance computers.
[src:x10-language/ibm] On April 7, 1964, IBM launched the first computer system family, the IBM System/360.
[src:x10-language/ibm] It spanned the complete range of commercial and scientific applications from large to small, allowing companies for the first time to upgrade to models with greater computing capability without having to rewrite their applications.
[src:x10-language/ibm] It was followed by the IBM System/370 in 1970.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Together the 360 and 370 made the IBM mainframe the dominant mainframe computer and the dominant computing platform in the industry throughout this period and into the early 1980s.
[src:x10-language/ibm] They and the operating systems that ran on them such as OS/VS1 and MVS, and the middleware built on top of those such as the CICS transaction processing monitor, had a near-monopoly-level market share and became the thing IBM was most known for during this period.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Shortly after, IBM unbundled its software and services in what many observers believed was a direct result of the lawsuit, creating a competitive market for software.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1982, the Department of Justice dropped the case as "without merit".
[src:x10-language/ibm] Also in 1969, IBM engineer Forrest Parry invented the magnetic stripe card that would become ubiquitous for credit/debit/ATM cards, driver's licenses, rapid transit cards and a multitude of other identity and access control applications.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM pioneered the manufacture of these cards, and for most of the 1970s, the data processing systems and software for such applications ran exclusively on IBM computers.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Laurer developed the Universal Product Code.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM and the World Bank first introduced financial swaps to the public in 1981, when it entered into a swap agreement.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In the early 1970s, the Examination Department of the South Vietnamese Ministry of Education contracted with IBM to computerize all examination records, from registration and application forms to certificates of admission and necessary statistical data.
[src:x10-language/ibm] By 1974, all subjects in the South Vietnamese high school graduation exam were converted to multiple-choice questions.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Answer sheets for the multiple-choice exams were ordered from the United States, and candidates' papers were graded using an IBM 1230 machine.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The graded papers were then transferred to an IBM 534 machine for punching.
[src:x10-language/ibm] These punched sheets were then fed into an IBM 360 machine to read the scores, multiply by coefficients, add up the scores, calculate the average score, standard deviation, convert raw scores to standardized scores, and calculate the admission ranking.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The sample group and norm group were carefully selected according to statistical methods to calculate the average score and standard deviation.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM entered the microcomputer market in the 1980s with the IBM Personal Computer (IBM 5150).
[src:x10-language/ibm] The computer, which spawned a long line of successors, had a profound influence on the development of the personal computer market and became one of IBM's best selling products of all time.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The PC was not well protected by intellectual property laws.
[src:x10-language/ibm] As a consequence, IBM quickly began losing its market dominance to emerging, compatible competitors in the PC market.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Experts debate whether this was an early example of successful adoption of open architecture, or a lack of business foresight by IBM.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1985, IBM collaborated with Microsoft to develop a new operating system, which was released as OS/2.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Following a dispute, Microsoft severed the collaboration and IBM continued development of OS/2 on its own but it failed in the marketplace against Microsoft's Windows during the mid-1990s.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1991, IBM began spinning off its many divisions into autonomous subsidiaries (so-called "Baby Blues") in an attempt to make the company more manageable and to streamline IBM by having other investors finance those companies.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Lexmark was acquired by Clayton & Dubilier in a leveraged buyout shortly after its formation.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1997, Deep Blue, a chess computer created by IBM beat Chess World Champion at the time, Garry Kasparov in a six round match following standard tournament rules.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In September 1992, IBM finished spinning off its various microcomputer personal computer manufacturing divisions and were consolidated into an autonomous wholly owned subsidiary known as the IBM Personal Computer Company (IBM PC Co.).
[src:x10-language/ibm] This corporate restructuring came after IBM reported a sharp drop in profit margins during the second quarter of fiscal year 1992; market analysts attributed the drop to a fierce price war in the personal computer market over the summer of 1992.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The corporate restructuring was one of the largest and most expensive in history up to that point.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM PC Co. introduced the ThinkPad clone computers, which IBM would heavily market and would eventually become one of the best-selling series of notebook computers.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1993, IBM posted an $8 billion loss – at the time the biggest in American corporate history.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Lou Gerstner was hired as CEO from RJR Nabisco to turn the company around.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1995, IBM purchased Lotus Development Corporation, best known for its Lotus 1-2-3 spreadsheet software.
[src:x10-language/ibm] During the decade, IBM was working on a new operating system, named the Workplace OS project.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Despite a large amount of money spent on the project, it was cancelled in 1996.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1998, IBM merged the enterprise-oriented Personal Systems Group of the IBM PC Co. into IBM's own Global Services personal computer consulting and customer service division.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The resulting merged business units then became known simply as IBM Personal Systems Group.
[src:x10-language/ibm] A year later, IBM stopped selling its computers at retail outlets after its market share in this sector had fallen considerably behind competitors Compaq and Dell.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Immediately afterwards, the IBM PC Co. was dissolved and merged into IBM Personal Systems Group.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In the 2000s, IBM collaborated with the Chinese defense contractor Huadi to develop the “Golden Shield Project”, a large-scale policing and surveillance project in Beijing.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The system was reportedly used to monitor online activity and target groups such as Falun Gong, Uyghurs and other individuals considered security risks.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2002, IBM acquired PwC Consulting, the consulting arm of PwC which was merged into its IBM Global Services.
[src:x10-language/ibm] On September 14, 2004, LG and IBM announced that their business alliance in the South Korean market would end at the end of that year.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Both companies stated that it was unrelated to the charges of bribery earlier that year.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Xnote was originally part of the joint venture and was sold by LG in 2012.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Continuing a trend started in the 1990s of downsizing its operations and divesting from commodity production, IBM sold all of its personal computer business to Chinese technology company Lenovo, and in 2009, it acquired software company SPSS Inc.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Later in 2009, IBM's Blue Gene supercomputing program was awarded the National Medal of Technology and Innovation by U.S.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2011, an IBM-owned artificial intelligence program called Watson was exhibited on *Jeopardy!* where it won against game-show champions Ken Jennings and Brad Rutter.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company also celebrated its 100th anniversary in the same year on June 16.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2012, IBM announced it had agreed to buy Kenexa and Texas Memory Systems, and a year later it also acquired SoftLayer Technologies, a web hosting service, in a deal worth around $2 billion.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Also that year, the company designed a video surveillance system for Davao City.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2014, IBM announced it would sell its x86 server division to Lenovo for $2.1 billion while continuing to offer Power ISA-based servers.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Also that year, IBM began announcing several major partnerships with other companies, including Apple Inc., Twitter, Facebook, Tencent, Cisco, UnderArmour, Box, Microsoft, VMware, CSC, Macy's, Sesame Workshop, the parent company of Sesame Street, and Salesforce.com.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2015, its chip division transitioned to a fabless model with semiconductors design, offloading manufacturing to GlobalFoundries.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2015, IBM announced three major acquisitions: Merge Healthcare for $1 billion, data storage vendor Cleversafe, and all digital assets from The Weather Company, including Weather.com and The Weather Channel mobile app.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Also that year, IBM employees created the film *A Boy and His Atom*, which was the first molecule movie to tell a story.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2016, IBM acquired video conferencing service Ustream and formed a new cloud video unit.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In April 2016, it posted a 14-year low in quarterly sales.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The following month, Groupon sued IBM accusing it of patent infringement, two months after IBM accused Groupon of patent infringement in a separate lawsuit.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2016, IBM bought Truven Health Analytics for $2.6 billion.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In October 2018, IBM announced its intention to acquire Red Hat for $34 billion, which was completed on July 9, 2019.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In February 2020, IBM's John Kelly III joined Brad Smith of Microsoft to sign a pledge with the Vatican to ensure the ethical use and practice of Artificial Intelligence (AI).
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM announced in October 2020 that it would divest the Managed Infrastructure Services unit of its Global Technology Services division into a new public company.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The new company, Kyndryl, will have 90,000 employees, 4,600 clients in 115 countries, with an order backlog of $60 billion.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM's spin-off was greater than any of its previous divestitures, and welcomed by investors.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM appointed Martin Schroeter, who had been IBM's CFO from 2014 through the end of 2017, as CEO of Kyndryl.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2021, IBM announced the acquisition of the enterprise software company Turbonomic for $1.5 billion.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In January 2022, IBM announced it would sell Watson Health to private equity firm Francisco Partners.
[src:x10-language/ibm] On March 7, 2022, a few days after the start of the Russian invasion of Ukraine, IBM CEO Arvind Krishna announced that "we have suspended all business in Russia".
[src:x10-language/ibm] All Russian articles were also removed from the IBM website.
[src:x10-language/ibm] On June 7, Krishna announced that IBM would carry out an "orderly wind-down" of its operations in Russia.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In late 2022, IBM started a collaboration with new Japanese manufacturer Rapidus, which led GlobalFoundries to file a lawsuit against IBM the following year.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2023, IBM acquired Manta Software Inc. to complement its data and A.I. governance capabilities for an undisclosed amount.
[src:x10-language/ibm] On November 16, 2023, IBM suspended ads on Twitter after ads were found next to pro-Nazi content.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In August 2023, IBM agreed to sell The Weather Company to Francisco Partners for an undisclosed sum.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The sale was finalized on February 1, 2024, and the price was disclosed as $1.1 billion, with $750 million in cash, $100 million deferred over seven years, and $250 million in contingent consideration.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In December 2023, IBM announced it would acquire Software AG's StreamSets and webMethods platforms for €2.13 billion ($2.33 billion).
[src:x10-language/ibm] On December 8, 2025, IBM announced a deal to acquire data-infrastructure company Confluent for approximately $11 billion.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The deal closed in March 2026 and was expected to help further advance the company's interests in AI.
[src:x10-language/ibm] On June 25, 2026, IBM unveiled the world's first technology capable of producing chips smaller than 1 nanometer.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM's market capitalization was valued at over $153 billion as of May 2024.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Despite its relative decline within the technology sector, IBM remains the seventh largest technology company by revenue, and 68th largest overall company by revenue in the United States.
[src:x10-language/ibm] 38 on the 2020 Fortune 500 rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2014, IBM was accused of using "financial engineering" to hit its quarterly earnings targets rather than investing for the longer term.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2018, IBM along with 91 additional *Fortune* 500 companies had "paid an effective federal tax rate of 0% or less" as a result of the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM Q1 2024 revenue alone was $14.5 billion, up 1% year-over-year.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company's software revenue was up 5% with strong performance in hybrid cloud and AI.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The full FY2024 figure and FY2024 figure and FY2025 quarterly results need updating throughout the article.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company's 15-member board of directors are responsible for overall corporate management and includes the current or former CEOs of Anthem, Dow Chemical, Johnson and Johnson, Royal Dutch Shell, UPS, and Vanguard as well as the president of Cornell University and a retired U.S.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Vanguard Group is the largest shareholder of IBM and as of March 31, 2023, held 15.7% of total shares outstanding.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2011, IBM became the first technology company Warren Buffett's holding company Berkshire Hathaway invested in.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Initially he bought 64 million shares costing $10.5 billion.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Over the years, Buffett increased his IBM holdings, but by the end of 2017 had reduced them by 94.5% to 2.05 million shares; by May 2018, he was completely out of IBM.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM is headquartered in Armonk, New York, a community 37 miles (60 km) north of Midtown Manhattan.
[src:x10-language/ibm] A nickname for the company is the "**Colossus of Armonk**".
[src:x10-language/ibm] Its principal building, referred to as CHQ, is a 283,000-square-foot (26,300 m2) glass and stone edifice on a 25-acre (10 ha) parcel amid a 432-acre former apple orchard the company purchased in the mid-1950s.
[src:x10-language/ibm] There are two other IBM buildings within walking distance of CHQ: the North Castle office, which previously served as IBM's headquarters; and the Louis V.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Gerstner, Jr., Center for Learning (formerly known as IBM Learning Center (ILC)), a resort hotel and training center, which has 182 guest rooms, 31 meeting rooms, and various amenities.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM operates in 174 countries as of 2016, with mobility centers in smaller market areas and major campuses in the larger ones.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In New York City, IBM has several offices besides CHQ, including the IBM Watson headquarters at Astor Place in Manhattan.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Outside of New York, major campuses in the United States include Austin, Texas; Research Triangle Park (Raleigh-Durham), North Carolina; Rochester, Minnesota; and Silicon Valley, California.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM's real estate holdings are varied and globally diverse.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Towers occupied by IBM include 1250 René-Lévesque (Montreal, Canada) and One Atlantic Center (Atlanta, Georgia, US).
[src:x10-language/ibm] In Beijing, China, IBM occupies Pangu Plaza, the city's seventh tallest building and overlooking Beijing National Stadium ("Bird's Nest"), home to the 2008 Summer Olympics.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM India Private Limited is the Indian subsidiary of IBM, which is headquartered at Bangalore, Karnataka.
[src:x10-language/ibm] It has facilities in Coimbatore, Chennai, Kochi, Ahmedabad, Delhi, Kolkata, Mumbai, Pune, Gurugram, Noida, Bhubaneshwar, Surat, Visakhapatnam, Hyderabad, Bangalore and Jamshedpur.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Defunct IBM campuses include the IBM Somers Office Complex (Somers, New York), Spango Valley (Greenock, Scotland), and Tour Descartes (Paris, France).
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company's contributions to industrial architecture and design include works by Marcel Breuer, Eero Saarinen, Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, I.M.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Van der Rohe's building in Chicago was recognized with the 1990 Honor Award from the National Building Museum.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2004, concerns were raised related to IBM's contribution in its early days to pollution in its original location in Endicott, New York.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM reported its total CO2e emissions (direct and indirect) for the twelve months ending December 31, 2020, at 621 kilotons (-324 /-34.3% year-on-year).
[src:x10-language/ibm] In February 2021, IBM committed to achieve net zero greenhouse gas emissions by the year 2030.
[src:x10-language/ibm] However, there is no evidence that IBM has actually made any substantial changes to actually do so.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM has a large and diverse portfolio of products and services.
[src:x10-language/ibm] As of 2016, these offerings fall into the categories of cloud computing, artificial intelligence, commerce, data and analytics, Internet of things (IoT), IT infrastructure, mobile, digital workplace and cybersecurity.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Since 1954, IBM has sold mainframe computers, the latest being the IBM z series.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The most recent model, the IBM z17, was released in 2025.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 1990, IBM released the Power microprocessors, which were designed into many console gaming systems, including Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, and Nintendo's Wii U.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2016, the company launched all-flash arrays designed for small and midsized companies, which includes software for data compression, provisioning, and snapshots across various systems.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In January 2019, IBM introduced its first commercial quantum computer: IBM Q System One.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In March 2020, it was announced that IBM would build Europe's first quantum data center in Ehningen, Germany.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The center, operated by the Fraunhofer Society, was opened in 2024.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Since 2009, IBM has owned SPSS, a software package used for statistical analysis in the social sciences.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM also owned The Weather Company, which provides weather forecasting and includes weather.com and Weather Underground, which was sold in 2024.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM Cloud includes infrastructure as a service (IaaS), software as a service (SaaS) and platform as a service (PaaS) offered through public, private and hybrid cloud delivery models.
[src:x10-language/ibm] For instance, the IBM Bluemix PaaS enables developers to quickly create complex websites on a pay-as-you-go model.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM SoftLayer is a dedicated server, managed hosting and cloud computing provider, which in 2011 reported hosting more than 81,000 servers for more than 26,000 customers.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM also provides Cloud Data Encryption Services (ICDES), using cryptographic splitting to secure customer data.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In May 2022, IBM announced the company had signed a multi-year Strategic Collaboration Agreement with Amazon Web Services to make a wide variety of IBM software available as a service on AWS Marketplace.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Additionally, the deal includes both companies making joint investments that make it easier for companies to consume IBM's offering and integrate them with AWS, including developer training and software development for select markets.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM Watson is a technology platform that uses natural language processing and machine learning to reveal insights from large amounts of unstructured data.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Watson was debuted in 2011 on the American game show *Jeopardy!*, where it competed against champions Ken Jennings and Brad Rutter in a three-game tournament and won.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Watson has since been applied to business, healthcare, developers, and universities.
[src:x10-language/ibm] For example, IBM has partnered with Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center to assist with considering treatment options for oncology patients and for doing melanoma screenings.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Several companies use Watson for call centers, either replacing or assisting customer service agents.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM also provides infrastructure for the New York City Police Department through its IBM Cognos Analytics to perform data visualizations of CompStat crime data.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In June 2020, IBM announced that it was exiting the facial recognition business.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In May 2023, IBM revealed Watsonx, a Generative AI toolkit that is powered by IBM's own Granite models with option to use other publicly available LLMs.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Watsonx has multiple services for training and fine tuning models based on confidential data.
[src:x10-language/ibm] A year later, IBM open-sourced Granite code models and put them on Hugging Face for public use.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In October 2024, IBM introduced Granite 3.0, an open-source large language model designed for enterprise AI applications.
[src:x10-language/ibm] With 160,000 consultants globally as of 2024, IBM is one of the ten largest consulting companies in the world, with capabilities spanning strategy and management consulting, experience design, technology and systems integration, and operations.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM's consulting business was valued at $20 billion, as of 2024.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Now, IBM Research constitutes the largest industrial research organization in the world, with 12 labs on 6 continents.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM Research is headquartered at the Thomas J.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In terms of investment, IBM's R&D expenditure totals several billion dollars each year.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2012, that expenditure was approximately $6.9 billion.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Recent allocations have included $1 billion to create a business unit for Watson in 2014, and $3 billion to create a next-gen semiconductor along with $4 billion towards growing the company's "strategic imperatives" (cloud, analytics, mobile, security, social) in 2015.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2024, IBM reported research and development expenditures of $7.48 billion, representing an increase of approximately 10.3% compared to the previous year’s expenditure of $6.78 billion.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM has been a leading proponent of the Open Source Initiative, and began supporting Linux in 1998.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company invests billions of dollars in services and software based on Linux through the IBM Linux Technology Center, which includes over 300 Linux kernel developers.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM's open source involvement has not been trouble-free, however (see *SCO v.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Additionally, in 1990 company scientists used a scanning tunneling microscope to arrange 35 individual xenon atoms to spell out the company initialism, marking the first structure assembled one atom at a time.
[src:x10-language/ibm] A major part of IBM research is the generation of patents.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Since its first patent for a traffic signaling device, IBM has been one of the world's most prolific patent sources.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2021, the company held the record for most patents generated by a business for 29 consecutive years for the achievement.
[src:x10-language/ibm] As of 2021, IBM holds the record for most annual U.S. patents generated by a business for 29 consecutive years.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In 2001, IBM became the first company to generate more than 3,000 patents in one year, beating this record in 2008 with over 4,000 patents.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM has also been criticized as being a patent troll.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM is nicknamed *Big Blue* partly because of its blue logo and color scheme, and also in reference to its former *de facto* dress code of white shirts with blue suits.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company logo has undergone several changes over the years, with its current "8-bar" logo designed in 1972 by graphic designer Paul Rand.
[src:x10-language/ibm] It was a general replacement for a 13-bar logo, since period photocopiers did not render narrow (as opposed to tall) stripes well.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Aside from the logo, IBM used Helvetica as a corporate typeface for 50 years, until it was replaced in 2017 by the custom-designed IBM Plex.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM has a valuable brand as a result of over 100 years of operations and marketing campaigns.
[src:x10-language/ibm] As a result, IBM CEO Ginni Rometty became the third female member of the Master's governing body, the Augusta National Golf Club.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM is also a major sponsor in professional tennis, with engagements at the U.S.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Open, Wimbledon, the Australian Open, and the French Open.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company also sponsored the Olympic Games from 1960 to 2000, and the National Football League from 2003 to 2012.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In Japan, IBM employees also have an American football team complete with pro stadium, cheerleaders and televised games, competing in the Japanese X-League as the "Big Blue".
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM is among the world's largest employers, with over 297,900 employees worldwide in 2022, with about 160,000 of those being tech consultants.
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM's leadership programs include Extreme Blue, an internship program, and the IBM Fellow award, offered since 1963 based on technical achievement.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Many IBM employees have achieved notability outside of work and after leaving IBM.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Other former IBM employees include NASA astronaut Michael J.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Massimino, Canadian astronaut and former Governor General Julie Payette, noted musician Dave Matthews, Harvey Mudd College president Maria Klawe, Western Governors University president emeritus Robert Mendenhall, former University of Kentucky president Lee T.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Todd Jr., former University of Iowa president Bruce Harreld, NFL referee Bill Carollo, former Rangers F.C. chairman John McClelland, and recipient of the Nobel Prize in Literature J.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Thomas Watson Jr. also served as the 11th national president of the Boy Scouts of America.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Five IBM employees have received the Nobel Prize: Leo Esaki, of the Thomas J.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Watson Research Center in Yorktown Heights, N.Y., in 1973, for work in semiconductors; Gerd Binnig and Heinrich Rohrer, of the Zurich Research Center, in 1986, for the scanning tunneling microscope; and Georg Bednorz and Alex Müller, also of Zurich, in 1987, for research in superconductivity.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Six IBM employees have won the Turing Award, including the first female recipient Frances E.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Ten National Medals of Technology and five National Medals of Science have been awarded to IBM employees.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Employees are often referred to as "IBMers" and "Once An IBMer, Always An IBMer.".
[src:x10-language/ibm] IBM's culture has evolved significantly over its century of operations.
[src:x10-language/ibm] In its early days, a dark (or gray) suit, white shirt, and a "sincere" tie constituted the public uniform for IBM employees.
[src:x10-language/ibm] During IBM's management transformation in the 1990s, CEO Louis V.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Gerstner Jr. relaxed these codes, normalizing the dress and behavior of IBM employees.
[src:x10-language/ibm] Similar IBM backronyms exist within the industry, such as Computerworld producing a badge labelled "It's Better Manually" implying it would be easier to use a paper-based system than a computer.
[src:x10-language/ibm] The company has traditionally resisted labor union organizing, although unions represent some IBM workers outside the United States.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:x10-language/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] In computer science, **partitioned global address space** (**PGAS**) is a parallel programming model paradigm.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] PGAS is typified by communication operations involving a global memory address space abstraction that is logically partitioned, where a portion is local to each process, thread, or processing element.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] The novelty of PGAS is that the portions of the shared memory space may have an affinity for a particular process, thereby exploiting locality of reference in order to improve performance.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] A PGAS memory model is featured in various parallel programming languages and libraries, including: Coarray Fortran, Unified Parallel C, Split-C, Fortress, Chapel, X10, UPC++, Coarray C++, Global Arrays, DASH and SHMEM.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] The PGAS paradigm is now an integrated part of the Fortran language, as of Fortran 2008 which standardized coarrays.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] The various languages and libraries offering a PGAS memory model differ widely in other details, such as the base programming language and the mechanisms used to express parallelism.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] Many PGAS systems combine the advantages of a SPMD programming style for distributed memory systems (as employed by MPI) with the data referencing semantics of shared memory systems.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] PGAS offers more efficiency and scalability than traditional shared-memory approaches with a flat address space, because hardware-specific data locality can be explicitly exposed in the semantic partitioning of the address space.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] A variant of the PGAS paradigm, **asynchronous partitioned global address space** (**APGAS**) augments the programming model with facilities for both local and remote asynchronous task creation.
[src:x10-language/partitioned-global-address-space] Two programming languages that use this model are Chapel and X10.
[src:x10-language/x10-programming-language] Its primary authors are Kemal Ebcioğlu, Saravanan Arumugam (Aswath), Vijay Saraswat, and Vivek Sarkar.
[src:x10-language/x10-programming-language] X10 is designed specifically for parallel computing using the partitioned global address space (PGAS) model.
[src:x10-language/x10-programming-language] A computation is divided among a set of *places*, each of which holds some data and hosts one or more *activities* that operate on those data.
[src:x10-language/x10-programming-language] It has a constrained type system for object-oriented programming, a form of dependent types.
[src:x10-language/x10-programming-language] Other features include user-defined primitive *struct* types; globally distributed *arrays*, and structured and unstructured parallelism.
[src:x10-language/x10-programming-language] X10 uses the concept of parent and child relationships for activities to prevent the lock stalemate that can occur when two or more processes wait for each other to finish before they can complete.
[src:x10-language/x10-programming-language] An activity may spawn one or more child activities, which may themselves have children.
[src:x10-language/x10-programming-language] Children cannot wait for a parent to finish, but a parent can wait for a child using the *finish* command.
